From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Date: Sat, 20 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] wasm: Phase 2 -- non-CLONE_VM fork() address-space dup (ABI v3)

Make a real non-CLONE_VM fork() work on the NOMMU wasm port. On NOMMU dup_mm()
memcpy's the parent mm_context but dup_mmap() copies no VMAs, so a stock fork
child has the parent's allocator scalars with an aliased free-list head and the
parent's owner pid. copy_thread() detects a fork (not CLONE_VM, parent runs a
private base-0 address space, child got a distinct mm), re-inits the child
free-list head + deep-copies the parent's freed extents (wasm_user_as_fork_dup),
and records the PARENT pid in user_as_fork_parent. The child's OWN pid is not yet
allocated in copy_thread (task_pid_nr(p) would read back as the parent's), so the
owner pid + the child Memory mint are deferred to the child's first __switch_to
(wasm_user_as_fork_finish), where the pid is final; it sets the owner pid and
mints the child's private Memory via the new wasm_user_mem_dup host import (the
runtime copies the bytes in the child worker AFTER instantiation -- a fresh
Instance re-applies active data segments). __switch_to reports fork_parent_pid to
the runtime (new wasm_create_and_run_task param) so the child worker duplicates
the AS and asyncify-rewinds the captured fork() stack instead of _start()-ing.

wasm_fork_current() is a new host->kernel export the runtime drives after the
user fork() stack has unwound; it is an ordinary kernel_clone(SIGCHLD, no
CLONE_VM) for current. Bumps WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI to 3 (matches runtime/hostbridge.js).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/entry.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/entry.h
index e6b0a5037..b393ce299 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/entry.h
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/entry.h
@@ -26,4 +26,12 @@ __visible unsigned long wasm_raised_irqs_ptr(int cpu);
 
 __visible void raise_exception(void);
 
+/*
+ * Phase 2 fork: host → kernel export. The runtime calls this on the forking
+ * task's worker after the user fork() stack has unwound, to allocate the child
+ * task/pid/mm (kernel_clone, SIGCHLD, no CLONE_VM). __visible so --export-all
+ * keeps it through gc-sections (like wasm_raised_irqs_ptr). Returns the child pid.
+ */
+__visible int wasm_fork_current(void);
+
 #endif /* _ASM_WASM_ENTRY_H */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h
index b91655808..64f990d69 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h
@@ -43,6 +43,14 @@ typedef struct {
 	 * (shared-fallback) memory. See wasm_user_as_pid() and the runtime flip.
 	 */
 	int			user_as_owner_pid;
+	/*
+	 * Phase 2 fork: set by copy_thread() on a non-CLONE_VM fork child to the
+	 * PARENT's pid (0 otherwise). __switch_to() reports it to the runtime so the
+	 * child worker duplicates the parent address space and asyncify-rewinds the
+	 * captured fork() stack instead of _start()-ing a fresh image. Read once at
+	 * the child's first run.
+	 */
+	int			user_as_fork_parent;
 } mm_context_t;
 
 #endif /* __ASSEMBLY__ */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h
index 6d40d18e2..9b90b3ef9 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h
@@ -71,4 +71,21 @@ void wasm_user_as_destroy(struct mm_struct *mm);
 void wasm_user_as_memzero(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long uaddr,
 			  unsigned long n);
 
+/*
+ * Phase 2 fork: turn `child` (a fresh non-CLONE_VM dup of `parent` — dup_mm()
+ * already memcpy'd the mm_context scalars) into an INDEPENDENT private address
+ * space. Re-inits the child free-list head (dup_mm aliased it to the parent's
+ * extents) and deep-copies the parent's freed extents. Keeps size/brk/live from
+ * the memcpy. Called from copy_thread() (child pid not yet allocated). Returns 0
+ * or -ENOMEM. Caller guards on wasm_user_as_active(parent) && child != parent.
+ */
+int wasm_user_as_fork_dup(struct mm_struct *child, struct mm_struct *parent);
+
+/*
+ * Phase 2 fork: finish the dup at the child's FIRST run (__switch_to), when its
+ * pid is final: record the child owner pid and mint its private Memory (sized
+ * from the child mm's user_as size) via wasm_user_mem_dup. Returns 0 or -ENOMEM.
+ */
+int wasm_user_as_fork_finish(struct mm_struct *mm, int child_pid);
+
 #endif /* _ASM_WASM_USER_AS_H */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
index befd83c79..f0daa4ec5 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
@@ -7,10 +7,11 @@
  * Cross-repo host-bridge ABI version. Must match the runtime
  * (runtime/hostbridge.js WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI). v1 = the uaccess copy ops
  * (0014/0015). v2 (Task 2) adds the per-process memory-lifecycle ops
- * (wasm_user_mem_create/grow/free) declared below. Bumped to 2 to match the
- * runtime that already ships the v2 ops.
+ * (wasm_user_mem_create/grow/free) declared below. v3 (Phase 2 fork) adds
+ * wasm_user_mem_dup + the fork_parent_pid channel on wasm_create_and_run_task
+ * + the wasm_fork_current export. Bumped to 3 to match the runtime.
  */
-#define WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI 2
+#define WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI 3
 
 /* These are symbols imported from the Wasm host. */
 
@@ -56,6 +57,18 @@ extern long          wasm_user_mem_create(int pid, unsigned long init_pages);
 extern unsigned long wasm_user_mem_grow(int pid, unsigned long delta_pages);
 extern void          wasm_user_mem_free(int pid);
 
+/*
+ * Phase 2 fork (ABI v3): mint the fork child `child_pid`'s private base-0
+ * WebAssembly.Memory with the SAME page count as `parent_pid`'s, registered
+ * under child_pid. MINTS ONLY — the verbatim byte copy is the runtime's job,
+ * done in the child worker after it instantiates (a fresh Instance re-applies
+ * active data segments, which would clobber a pre-copied .bss). Takes the SIZE
+ * (not the parent pid) so the mint needs no parent registry lookup — it runs in
+ * __switch_to, possibly in a worker without the parent's Memory entry. Returns 0
+ * on success, <0 on failure.
+ */
+extern long          wasm_user_mem_dup(int child_pid, unsigned long init_pages);
+
 extern void wasm_start_cpu(unsigned int cpu, struct task_struct *idle_task);
 extern void wasm_stop_cpu(unsigned int cpu);
 
@@ -66,11 +79,17 @@ extern void wasm_stop_cpu(unsigned int cpu);
  * worker that pid's private Memory. 0 = a fresh mm (the task will exec and mint
  * its own). Only meaningful with the wasm_user_as allocator on.
  */
+/*
+ * `fork_parent_pid` (Phase 2): nonzero ⇒ this new task is a non-CLONE_VM fork
+ * child of that pid. The runtime duplicates the parent's address space into the
+ * child and asyncify-rewinds the captured fork() stack (so fork() returns 0 in
+ * the child) instead of _start()-ing a fresh image. 0 = exec / CLONE_VM / kthread.
+ */
 extern struct task_struct *wasm_create_and_run_task(
 	struct task_struct *prev_task, struct task_struct *new_task,
 	const char *name, unsigned long bin_start, unsigned long bin_end,
 	unsigned long data_start, unsigned long table_start,
-	int mm_owner_pid);
+	int mm_owner_pid, int fork_parent_pid);
 extern void wasm_release_task(struct task_struct *dead_task);
 extern struct task_struct *wasm_serialize_tasks(struct task_struct *prev_task,
 	struct task_struct *next_task);
diff --git a/arch/wasm/kernel/process.c b/arch/wasm/kernel/process.c
index 9b9e66610..1b7c16125 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/kernel/process.c
+++ b/arch/wasm/kernel/process.c
@@ -4,11 +4,14 @@
 #include <linux/ptrace.h>
 #include <linux/sched.h>
 #include <linux/sched/debug.h>
+#include <linux/sched/task.h>		/* Phase 2: kernel_clone(), kernel_clone_args */
 #include <linux/sched/task_stack.h>
+#include <linux/signal.h>		/* Phase 2: SIGCHLD */
 #include <linux/printk.h>
 #include <asm/cpuflags.h>
 #include <asm/entry.h>
 #include <asm/wasm.h>
+#include <asm/user_as.h>		/* Phase 2: wasm_user_as_active/_fork_dup */
 
 static cpumask_t user_cpus = CPU_MASK_NONE;
 
@@ -56,6 +59,7 @@ __switch_to(struct task_struct *prev_task, struct task_struct *next_task)
 	unsigned long bin_end = 0U;
 	unsigned long data_start = 0U;
 	int mm_owner_pid = 0;	/* Task 2.3: see wasm_create_and_run_task */
+	int fork_parent_pid = 0;	/* Phase 2: 0 = not a fork (see below) */
 
 	if (task_thread_info(next_task)->flags & _TIF_NEVER_RUN) {
 		task_thread_info(next_task)->flags &= ~_TIF_NEVER_RUN;
@@ -76,6 +80,21 @@ __switch_to(struct task_struct *prev_task, struct task_struct *next_task)
 			 * mm's private Memory instead of a fresh one. A fresh task
 			 * (mm not yet live) gets 0 and mints its own at exec.
 			 */
+			/*
+			 * Phase 2 fork: copy_thread set user_as_fork_parent on a
+			 * non-CLONE_VM fork child (the parent pid). This is the child's
+			 * FIRST run and its pid is now final, so finish the dup here:
+			 * record the child owner pid + mint its private Memory (sized to
+			 * the parent's) BEFORE wasm_create_and_run_task forwards it. Then
+			 * report fork_parent_pid so the runtime duplicates the parent AS
+			 * and asyncify-rewinds the captured fork() stack instead of
+			 * _start()-ing a fresh image.
+			 */
+			fork_parent_pid = next_task->mm->context.user_as_fork_parent;
+			if (fork_parent_pid)
+				wasm_user_as_fork_finish(next_task->mm,
+					task_pid_nr(next_task));
+
 			if (next_task->mm->context.user_as_live)
 				mm_owner_pid =
 					next_task->mm->context.user_as_owner_pid;
@@ -83,7 +102,8 @@ __switch_to(struct task_struct *prev_task, struct task_struct *next_task)
 
 		/* This is called instead of serialize the first time. */
 		last_task = wasm_create_and_run_task(prev_task, next_task, name,
-			bin_start, bin_end, data_start, 0U, mm_owner_pid);
+			bin_start, bin_end, data_start, 0U, mm_owner_pid,
+			fork_parent_pid);
 	} else {
 		last_task = wasm_serialize_tasks(prev_task, next_task);
 	}
@@ -212,9 +232,68 @@ int copy_thread(struct task_struct *p, const struct kernel_clone_args *args)
 		current->mm->end_data = 0;
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Phase 2 fork: a non-CLONE_VM clone from a user task that runs a private
+	 * base-0 address space is a real fork() — the child needs a DUPLICATE of
+	 * the parent's private memory. On NOMMU, dup_mm() memcpy'd the parent
+	 * mm_context verbatim (carrying user_as_size/brk/live) but left two things
+	 * wrong for a separate address space, and dup_mmap() copied no VMAs; fix the
+	 * allocator state and mint the child's private Memory here (the verbatim
+	 * BYTE copy is the runtime's job — finding A defers it to the child worker).
+	 *
+	 * Guard: only when (a) NOT CLONE_VM (a thread shares the mm — handled by the
+	 * owner-pid path, not here), (b) the parent's mm has a live private AS, and
+	 * (c) the child got a distinct mm (it did: !CLONE_VM ⇒ dup_mm). kthreads
+	 * (no mm) and the flag-off default fall through untouched.
+	 */
+	if (!(args->flags & CLONE_VM) && wasm_user_as_active(current->mm) &&
+	    p->mm && p->mm != current->mm) {
+		int rc = wasm_user_as_fork_dup(p->mm, current->mm);
+		if (rc)
+			return rc;
+		/*
+		 * Record the PARENT pid (valid now; the child's own pid is not yet
+		 * allocated in copy_thread — it would read back as the parent's). The
+		 * child owner pid + Memory mint happen at the child's first __switch_to
+		 * (wasm_user_as_fork_finish), where its pid is final. Nonzero here also
+		 * tells __switch_to this is a fork child.
+		 */
+		p->mm->context.user_as_fork_parent = task_pid_nr(current);
+		/*
+		 * Resume in USER mode. A normal clone copies the parent's pt_regs
+		 * cpuflags as saved by SYSCALL ENTRY (user mode, to be restored on
+		 * exit). fork() here is driven host-side (wasm_fork_current), bypassing
+		 * syscall entry, so the parent's saved cpuflags may be stale/kernel —
+		 * which would trip "Syscall called when in kernel mode" on the child's
+		 * first syscall after the asyncify rewind. The child resumes user code,
+		 * so force the user-task default explicitly.
+		 */
+		child_pt_regs->cpuflags = CPUFLAGS_USER_TASK_DEFAULT;
+	}
+
 	return user_task_set_affinity(p);
 }
 
+/*
+ * Phase 2 fork: host → kernel export (auto-exported by --export-all). The
+ * runtime calls this on the FORKING task's worker AFTER the user instance has
+ * unwound its fork() stack (asyncify), to allocate the child task/pid/mm. It is
+ * an ordinary kernel_clone() for `current` with SIGCHLD and no CLONE_VM, so
+ * copy_thread() (above) runs the fork mm-dup. Returns the child pid (or -errno).
+ * The child task spawns LAZILY via the normal __switch_to → wasm_create_and_run_
+ * task path; the runtime's fork-time memory snapshot (taken before this returns)
+ * decouples the byte copy from when the child actually runs, so no special
+ * scheduler drive is needed here.
+ */
+__visible int wasm_fork_current(void)
+{
+	struct kernel_clone_args args = {
+		.exit_signal = SIGCHLD,
+	};
+
+	return kernel_clone(&args);
+}
+
 /*
  * Set up a thread for executing a new program.
  */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c b/arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c
index b0d66b5a1..ff74d48db 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c
+++ b/arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c
@@ -95,6 +95,65 @@ int wasm_user_as_init(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long size_bytes)
 	return 0;
 }
 
+int wasm_user_as_fork_dup(struct mm_struct *child, struct mm_struct *parent)
+{
+	struct user_as_extent *e, *tmp;
+
+	/*
+	 * dup_mm() memcpy'd parent->context into child->context, so the scalars
+	 * (user_as_size, user_as_brk, user_as_live) are already correct for a
+	 * verbatim address-space copy. But child->context.user_as_free is a memcpy
+	 * of the parent's list_head, so its prev/next still point at the PARENT's
+	 * extent nodes — drained as-is at the child's exit_mmap that would kfree the
+	 * parent's nodes (UAF / double-free). Re-init the head, then DEEP-COPY each
+	 * parent extent so the child reuses the same freed offsets independently.
+	 *
+	 * The owner pid + the child Memory MINT are NOT done here: this runs in
+	 * copy_thread(), BEFORE the child's pid is allocated (task_pid_nr(p) would
+	 * return the PARENT's pid). They are done in __switch_to() (the child's first
+	 * run), where the child pid is final — see wasm_user_as_fork_finish().
+	 */
+	INIT_LIST_HEAD(&child->context.user_as_free);
+	list_for_each_entry(e, &parent->context.user_as_free, list) {
+		struct user_as_extent *ne = kmalloc(sizeof(*ne), GFP_KERNEL);
+
+		if (!ne)
+			goto nomem;
+		ne->start = e->start;
+		ne->len = e->len;
+		list_add_tail(&ne->list, &child->context.user_as_free);
+	}
+	return 0;
+
+nomem:
+	list_for_each_entry_safe(e, tmp, &child->context.user_as_free, list) {
+		list_del(&e->list);
+		kfree(e);
+	}
+	return -ENOMEM;
+}
+
+int wasm_user_as_fork_finish(struct mm_struct *mm, int child_pid)
+{
+	/*
+	 * Called from __switch_to() the first time a fork child runs, when its pid
+	 * is final. The child owns a DISTINCT private Memory: record the owner pid
+	 * (so its uaccess resolves the child entry, not the parent's) and mint that
+	 * Memory at the child mm's user_as SIZE — which dup_mm() memcpy'd from the
+	 * parent, and which the runtime's verbatim snapshot fills. We pass the SIZE
+	 * (not the parent pid): __switch_to may run in a worker that does NOT hold
+	 * the parent's Memory entry (when one fork child schedules the next), so the
+	 * mint must not need a parent lookup. The byte copy happens in the child
+	 * worker AFTER instantiation (finding A).
+	 */
+	unsigned long pages = mm->context.user_as_size / WASM_PAGE_SIZE;
+
+	mm->context.user_as_owner_pid = child_pid;
+	if (wasm_user_mem_dup(child_pid, pages) < 0)
+		return -ENOMEM;
+	return 0;
+}
+
 /*
  * First-fit the free-list. On an exact-or-larger hit, carve `len` off the FRONT
  * of the extent (so callers get the lowest offset; the tail stays free).
